response:
 The probability of getting exactly k heads in m flips of an unfair coin is given by the binomial distribution:

{eq}\begin{align}

P(X=k)&=\left(\begin{array}{c}m\\k\end{array}\right)q^{k}(1-q)^{m-k}

\end{align}

{/eq}

where $q$ is the probability of getting heads on a single flip.

In this case, $m=8$, $q=\frac{2}{3}$, so the probability of getting exactly $k$ heads is:

{eq}\begin{align}

P(X=k)&=\left(\begin{array}{c}8\\k\end{array}\right)\left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{k}\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)^{8-k}

\end{align}

{/eq}

The probability of getting exactly $k$ heads is proportional to $(2/3)^{k}$, which means that:

{eq}\begin{align}

P(X=3)&\propto \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{3}\\&=\frac{8}{27}\\

P(X=2)&\propto \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)^{2}\\&=\frac{4}{9}\\

\frac{P(X=3)}{P(X=2)}&=\frac{8/27}{4/9}\\&=\frac{2}{3}\\

\end{align}

{/eq}

So the probability of getting exactly three heads is $\frac{2}{3}$ times as high as the probability of getting exactly two heads. This gives a revised answer of one.
